The maximum age corresponds to the point where the measured decay rate is at the lower limit of the error margin, which is \(15.3 - 0.1 = 15.2\) disintegrations per minute per gram of carbon. The formula for radioactive decay is: \[ A = A_0 \cdot e^{-\lambda t} \] where \(A\) is the current activity, \(A_0\) is the original activity, \(\lambda\) is the decay constant, and \(t\) is the time elapsed. First, we calculate the decay constant \(\lambda\) using the half-life: \[ \lambda = \frac{\ln(2)}{T_{1/2}} = \frac{\ln(2)}{5730} \approx 0.000120968 \text{ per year} \] We solve for \(t\) when \(A = 15.2\) and \(A_0 = 15.3\): \[ 15.2 = 15.3 \cdot e^{-\lambda t} \] \[ \frac{15.2}{15.3} = e^{-\lambda t} \] Taking the natural logarithm of both sides: \[ \ln\left(\frac{15.2}{15.3}\right) = -\lambda t \] \[ t = \frac{\ln\left(\frac{15.3}{15.2}\right)}{\lambda} \] Substituting the values: \[ t = \frac{\ln(1.0065789)}{0.000120968} \approx \frac{0.00655}{0.000120968} \approx 54.3 \text{ years} \] Thus, the maximum age of a sample that can be dated, considering the measurement error, is approximately \(\boxed{54}\) years.
